        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>A Request for Information (RFI) is a formal question from a contractor to the design team or owner — asking for clarification on drawings, specifications, or project requirements. An open RFI on a critical item means work stops until the answer comes. Poor RFI management — slow routing, lost questions, undocumented responses — is a primary driver of construction delays and disputes.</p>

        <p>Good RFI software makes the process fast, traceable, and defensible when schedule impact needs to be documented.</p>

        <h2>What good RFI management requires</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Formal logging:</strong> Every RFI gets a number, date, subject, question, and required response date</li>
          <li><strong>Routing workflow:</strong> RFI reaches the right party (architect, structural engineer, owner) without getting lost in email</li>
          <li><strong>Response tracking:</strong> System records when the question was received, who it went to, and when it was answered</li>
          <li><strong>Drawing links:</strong> RFIs linked to the specific drawing and detail being questioned</li>
          <li><strong>Impact documentation:</strong> Ability to attach a cost or schedule impact to the RFI when applicable</li>
          <li><strong>Distribution:</strong> Answered RFIs distributed to affected subs and field teams automatically</li>
          <li><strong>Reporting:</strong> Open RFI log for project status reviews; overdue RFI tracking for follow-up</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Best software for RFI management</h2>

        <h3>Procore — Best enterprise RFI workflow</h3>
        <p>Procore's RFI module is the gold standard for commercial construction. RFIs are numbered, linked to drawings, routed to the appropriate design professional, tracked through response, and connected to the drawing set when revisions follow. The audit trail shows every action on every RFI — who received it, when, what they did with it, and when they responded. For large commercial projects with hundreds of RFIs and contractual implications attached to response times, Procore's documentation is invaluable.</p>

        <p>GCs on Procore can manage RFIs with subcontractors and the design team in the same platform, creating a single source of truth for all project questions. Subs access Procore through the free sub portal to submit and receive RFIs without a separate subscription.</p>

        <h3>Autodesk Build — Best BIM-connected RFIs</h3>
        <p>Autodesk Build connects RFIs to the BIM model through the Autodesk Construction Cloud. When an RFI concerns a coordination conflict between structural and mechanical at a specific location, the RFI can be linked to the model location and the relevant Revit elements. For design-build projects and projects with active BIM coordination, this model linkage makes RFIs more precise and easier for the design team to answer correctly the first time.</p>

        <h3>Fieldwire — Best for field-initiated RFIs</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire's RFI tool is optimized for the field. A superintendent reviewing drawings in the field can initiate an RFI directly from the plan, attaching a photo of the site condition and tagging the plan location. The RFI routes to the office for formal submission to the design team. For GCs where most RFIs originate in the field rather than in the estimating room, Fieldwire's field-to-office flow works well.</p>

        <h3>Buildertrend — Best for residential RFI management</h3>
        <p>Residential construction has fewer formal RFIs than commercial work, but questions to architects, structural engineers, and homeowners still need to be tracked. Buildertrend's communication and document management tools handle informal RFI workflows — questions logged to the project, responses documented, and any drawing revisions distributed to field teams. It's not a formal AIA-compliant RFI system, but for residential work the formal structure isn't necessary.</p>

