        <h2>RFI best practices that software enables</h2>

        <h3>Submit early</h3>
        <p>The worst time to submit an RFI is the day before you need the answer. Good project management means identifying questions from the drawing set before that section of work begins — ideally in preconstruction or at the project startup review. Software that links RFIs to the project schedule helps project managers identify which RFIs are approaching critical deadlines.</p>

        <h3>Be specific and include context</h3>
        <p>Vague RFIs get vague answers, which often generate follow-up RFIs. Good RFI software includes fields for drawing number, detail number, specification section, and a specific question with clear context. Photos of conflicting field conditions attached to the RFI reduce the back-and-forth.</p>

        <h3>Track response time contractually</h3>
        <p>Many construction contracts specify response time requirements for RFIs (often 5–7 business days). If the design team takes 21 days to answer an RFI that delayed your work, that delay may be a compensable event. But only if you have documentation of when the RFI was submitted and when it was answered. Software creates this documentation automatically; email threads do not create reliable, defensible records.</p>

        <h3>Distribute answers proactively</h3>
        <p>An answered RFI that stays in the project management system without reaching the field crew who needs the information is worthless. RFI software should route responses to the appropriate subs and field teams automatically when the RFI is answered — not require a separate step to distribute.</p>

        <h2>RFIs and schedule impact documentation</h2>
        <p>When an RFI delays work, that delay may be billable as a time impact. Documenting the connection between an unanswered RFI and a work stoppage requires:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The RFI submission date and the response date</li>
          <li>Daily logs showing that affected work was held pending the RFI response</li>
          <li>A schedule impact analysis showing how the work delay affected the critical path</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Construction software that connects daily logs, the project schedule, and RFI tracking in one system makes this documentation straightforward. Separate systems require manual correlation that's hard to defend under scrutiny.</p>

        <h2>Bottom line</h2>
        <p>For commercial GCs doing formal construction administration, Procore or Autodesk Build are the best RFI management tools. For residential builders and remodelers, Buildertrend's communication tools handle informal RFI workflows adequately. The most important thing is having any systematic process — contractors who track RFIs through email with no formal logging consistently experience more delays, more disputes, and poorer schedule outcomes than those with systematic tracking.</p>

